Joe receives a cake for his birthday. He eats $\frac{1}{4}$ of the cake on the first day. On the second day, he eats $\frac{3}{4}$ of the amount of cake that is left after the first day. What fraction of a whole cake is left for Joe to eat on the third day?

}

\textbf{Answer:} Using the common denominator of $4$, we can determine that after the first day, Joe has$$1-\frac{1}{4}=\frac{4}{4}-\frac{1}{4}=\frac{4-1}{4}=\frac{3}{4}$$of the cake left. On the second day, Joe eats $\frac{3}{4}$ of the amount of cake that is left after the first day, or$$\frac{3}{4}\cdot \frac{3}{4}=\frac{9}{16}$$of the whole cake. Therefore, using a common denominator of $16$ we can see that$$\frac{3}{4}-\frac{9}{16}=\frac{3}{4}\cdot \frac{4}{4}-\frac{9}{16}=\frac{12}{16}-\frac{9}{16}=\frac{12-9}{16}=\boxed{\frac{3}{16}}$$of the whole cake is left for Joe to eat on the third day.
